SDGs cover 17 development areas, encompassing three major pillars, namely, society, economy and environment. It is composed of an overall goal mechanism, including (1) ending poverty, (2) ending hunger, (3) healthy lives and well-being, (4) equitable quality education, (5) gender equality, (6) clean water and sanitation, (7) affordable and clean energy, (8) economic growth and decent work, (9) sustainable industrialization, innovation and resilient infrastructure facilities, (10) reduce inequality within and among countries, (11) sustainable cities and communities, (12) sustainable consumption and production, (13) climate action, (14) sustainable use of marine resources, (15) sustainable use of terrestrial ecosystems, (16) peaceful, just and powerful institutions, and (17) global partnership for sustainable development. So far, most research pertinent to SDGs has focused on the evaluation of synergies and trade-offs among SDGs and the predictions for the realization of SDGs, as well as further addition and expansion of research on the measurement indicators for SDGs. For example, Mainali, Luukkanen, Silveira, et al., by applying historical data from 1990 to 2012, analyzed the potential collaborative impact of different goals in six countries including Bangladesh, Nepal, Sri Lanka, Ghana, Ethiopia and Rwanda, created trans-departmental policies, and promoted collaborative mechanisms for realizing mutual goals [4•
                     ]. Pradhan, Costa, Rybski, et al., analyzed synergies and trade-offs of SDGs based on the global data set, compared positive and negative inter-relationships of each country’s SDGs, and proposed highlighted trade-offs that constituted obstacles to achieving the SDGs. All these concerns need to be negotiated and made structurally non-obstructive via deeper changes in the current strategies [5••
                     ]. Regarding the SDGs in Arab areas, Allen, Nejdawi, El-Baba, et al. conducted indicator-based assessments, and proceeded with a more in-depth exploration of interlinkages and dynamics among the SDGs [6•
                     ]. For the association between some specific SDGs, Shibata, Wilson, Watson, et al. interviewed the people from a landfill slum in eastern Indonesia in order to explore the relationship among poverty (SDG 1), education (SDG 4), sanitation (SDG 6) and health (SDG 3), illuminating that poverty directly or indirectly affects child health and eradicating extreme poverty remains the most critical challenge [7]. Similarly, Roy, Pramanick analyzed the interrelationship of water and sanitation (SDG 6) with health (SDG 3) and end to poverty (SDG 1) in India, the interrelation showing a positive impact of increasing per capita GDP on improving sanitation related indicators, reducing water and sanitation related diseases, especially in children and aged population [8]. Moreover, Joseph, Gunawan, Madi, et al. investigated the relationship between achieving SDGs and combatting corruption (SDG 16) in Malaysian and Indonesian, providing support for regulatory authorities to strengthen their integrity mechanisms [9].

Nhemachena, Matchaya, Nhemachena, et al. employed the arithmetic average cohesion method to calculate and compare agriculture-related SDGs Index in thirteen countries across South Africa [10••
                     ]. Campagnolo, Carraro, Eboli, et al. separated SDGs into three dimensions, that is, economy, society and environment, applied a comprehensive indicator (FEEM Sustainable Index) to evaluate the sustainability of diverse countries, and envisaged the index future through CGE models under varied policy situations [11•
                     ]. Likewise, Fullman, Barber, Abajobir, et al. measured the health-related SDGs in 188 countries [12]. Nhamo and Costanza, et al. conducted evaluation and prediction for the welfare effects of SDGs [13,14]. Srikanth, Mastrucci, Fuhrimann, Nauta, Hidayatno, et al. analyzed the impact of SDGs implementation on other industries, such as the relationship between SDG 7 (affordable and clean energy) and the power industry [15,16], the linkage between SDG 6 (clean water and sanitation) and wastewater treatment industry [17,18], and the association between industrial sustainable energy (SDG 9) and industry 4.0 technology [19]. In addition, some scholars contributed to enriching and stratifying SDGs, contributions like working out more detailed indicators, complementing indicators, improving measurement indicator methodology, establishing national indicator database, and collecting indicator data to carry out research and design [13,20–26].
